  "eprint": {
    "title": "One-One Constrained Pseudorandom Functions",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Naty Peter",
        "email": "naty@post",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Rotem Tsabary",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Hoeteck Wee",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "We define and study a new cryptographic primitive, named One-One Constrained Pseudorandom Functions. In this model there are two parties, Alice and Bob, that hold a common random string $K$, where Alice in addition holds a predicate $f:[N] \\rightarrow \\{ 0,1 \\}$ and Bob in addition holds an input $x \\in [N]$.\nWe then let Alice generate a key $K_f$ based on $f$ and $K$, and let Bob evaluate a value $K_x$ based on $x$ and $K$. We consider a third party that sees the values $(x,f,K_f)$ and the goal is to allow her to reconstruct $K_x$ whenever $f(x)=1$, while keeping $K_x$ pseudorandom whenever $f(x)=0$.\nThis primitive can be viewed as a relaxation of constrained PRFs, such that there is only a single key query and a single evaluation query.\n\n\nWe focus on the information-theoretic setting, where the one-one cPRF has perfect correctness and perfect security. Our main results are as follows.\n\n\n1. A Lower Bound. We show that in the information-theoretic setting, any one-one cPRF for punctured predicates is of exponential complexity (and thus the lower bound meets the upper bound that is given by a trivial construction). This stands in contrast with the well known GGM-based punctured PRF  from OWF, which is in particular a one-one cPRF. This also implies a similar lower bound for all NC1.\n\n2. New Constructions. On the positive side, we present efficient information-theoretic constructions of one-one cPRFs for a few other predicate families, such as equality predicates, inner-product predicates, and subset predicates. We also show a generic AND composition lemma that preserves complexity.\n\n3. An Amplification to standard cPRF. We show that all of our one-one cPRF constructions can be amplified to a standard (single-key) cPRF via any key-homomorphic PRF that supports linear computations. More generally, we suggest a new framework that we call the double-key model which allows to construct constrained PRFs via key-homomorphic PRFs.\n\n4. Relation to CDS. We show that one-one constrained PRFs imply conditional disclosure of secrets (CDS) protocols.\n\n\nWe believe that this simple model can be used to better understand constrained PRFs and related cryptographic primitives, and that further applications of one-one constrained PRFs and our double-key model will be found in the future, in addition to those we show in this paper.",
    "keywords": [
      "Constrained pseudorandom functions",
      "function secret-sharing",
      "conditional disclosure of secrets."
    ],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
